				September 15, 2013 12:01 a.m.
			


Fence-sitters key for Joseph Lhota
It's decision time for donors hesitant to embrace the Republican nominee.




				By
				
Chris  Bragg


















Comments

Email


Print




×



























Photo: Andrew Hawkins
Republican mayoral nominee Joseph Lhota will face off against Democratic candidate Bill de Blasio in the November election.





This Week in Crain's: September 16, 2013
Listen to the Podcast or Download









Last December, when Joseph Lhota resigned as chairman of the Metropolitan Transit Authority to launch a mayoral bid, many business leaders indicated they'd take a wait-and-see approach to his underdog candidacy. "In a city that is [heavily] Democratic, at a minimum the business community will be hedging its bets," explained Kathryn Wylde, president and CEO of the Partnership for New York City, an organization of the city's largest private employers. "It is still likely that the person who comes out of the Democratic primary will be the mayor." At the time, City Council Speaker Christine Quinn was perceived as Mayor Michael Bloomberg's business-friendly successor. But in last week's Democratic primary, Ms. Quinn placed a distant third, while the most liberal contender, Public Advocate Bill de Blasio, outpaced the field. Former city Comptroller Bill Thompson, who like Ms. Quinn is perceived as business-friendly, finished a distant second and may not even qualify for a runoff with Mr. de Blasio. 
article continues below advertisement

The results raise the question of whether the business community will move behind Mr. Lhota, despite his odds in a city with six Democrats for every Republican. Mr. Lhota had raised a total of $2 million as of late August, compared with Mr. de Blasio's $4.4 million. But Mr. de Blasio's tax-and-spend pledges may change that. "The real estate industry and others in New York have to be noticing Bill de Blasio's rhetoric," said Republican consultant Bill O'Reilly. "There's no going back to the center from where he is."

Friends supply funds
So far, business interests have wagered more on Mr. de Blasio, whose major campaign contributors, such as the real estate and taxi industries, have financial stakes in city policy. Mr. Lhota's biggest fundraisers have been former Giuliani administration colleagues. Of the 11 bundlers who have raised more than $10,000 for him, six worked in the administration with Mr. Lhota, who was deputy mayor and budget director. Many of them retain ties to city government. Mr. Lhota's biggest campaign bundler is Robert Harding, an attorney who has raised more than $41,000, much of it from his politically prominent law firm, Greenberg Traurig. Mr. Harding is the son of the late Liberal Party head Raymond Harding, who had extremely close ties with Mr. Giuliani and later pleaded guilty to securities violations in 2009. The son's appointment as Mr. Giuliani's budget director in 1998 raised eyebrows because he had little experience managing fiscal matters. Other major Lhota bundlers from the Giuliani world include former Deputy Mayor Randy Mastro, a politically connected attorney who, in classic bet-hedging style, was also a major bundler for the Democratic Mr. Thompson; Agostino Cangemi, an assistant counsel in the Giuliani administration who is now a lobbyist; John Odermatt, a former commissioner of the Office of Emergency Management and now a managing director at Citigroup; and John Mascialino, a former official in the Department of Citywide Administrative Services and an attorney who now heads Greenberg Traurig's government and law policy practice. Mr. Lhota's post-Giuliani stint as an executive vice president of Cablevision is also proving helpful in his run for mayor. The company's president and CEO, James Dolan, has raised more than $19,000, while Richard Hochman, a business consultant who is Mr. Lhota's second-biggest fundraiser, has served on Cablevision's board of directors. Mr. Hochman said he does not have business before the city that would benefit from a Lhota administration. He gave to Mr. Lhota, he added, because of their personal relationship and because he believes the candidate would preserve the gains of the Bloomberg and Giuliani eras. "I grew up in this city," Mr. Hochman said. "I saw it in 1969, I saw it in the 1980s, and for the past 20 years, Giuliani and Bloomberg made it such a better place to live. I don't want to go back." Given Mr. de Blasio's momentum, Mr. Lhota must reach beyond his inner circle, perhaps even to disaffected supporters of Mr. de Blasio's vanquished Democratic rivals. During the Republican primary, billionaire opponent John Catsimatidis repeatedly said that Mr. Lhota could not compete in November because of a lack of resources. Mr. Bloomberg, running as a Republican and independent, spent more than $100 million to eke out a third term in 2009.

Billionaire steps up
Mr. Lhota is getting help from an outside group called New Yorkers for Proven Leadership, which was started by three former Giuliani aides. It has already received $290,000 from billionaire David Koch and his wife and is launching a national fundraising effort touting Mr. Lhota as a moderate Republican who can win in a deep-blue city. Like Mr. Lhota's campaign, the committee might struggle to get enough donations to make a major impact, as New York Republicans have in recent statewide elections. But a spokesman for the group, Michael McKeon, said he believed business supporters of Ms. Quinn and Mr. Thompson would now flock to Mr. Lhota. "I think people who supported the other candidates are now going to take a harder look at a guy who is the most liberal candidate and the farthest to the left," said Mr. McKeon. "They're going to take a hard look at de Blasio. And they're going to take a second look at Joe." That will be an uphill fight, as the vanquished Democrats have all pledged to support their party's nominee. A number of Democrats crossed party lines to support Mr. Bloomberg in his 2005 and 2009 re-election campaigns, but Mr. Lhota lacks several advantages that the mayor had: incumbency, weak competition and an unlimited campaign budget. Mr. Lhota's third-largest fundraiser, Joseph Dussich of JAD Corp. of America, stands out as the rare business-owning Lhota bundler whose company might benefit from a Lhota mayoralty. Mr. Dussich, a Queens building maintenance supplies dealer who had raised more than $32,000 through July, received a visit from Mr. Lhota in August during a tour of small businesses. Mr. Lhota touted the mint-scented trash bags sold by Mr. Dussich that can repel mice, raccoons and other critters. During the visit, Mr. Dussich, who did not return a request for comment, lamented that the Parks Department was rebuffing his efforts to sell the trash bags to the city. Mr. Lhota called it the type of product that could keep manufacturing jobs in the city. "Of course you can, if you put your mind to it," Mr. Lhota said, according to The New York Times. "But you've got to think about what the products are that New Yorkers need."
A version of this article appears in the September 16, 2013, print issue of Crain's New York Business.


