N.Y. / Region

Amid Subway Crisis, Cuomo Taps an Old Hand to Head M.T.A.

By EMMA G. FITZSIMMONS and JESSE McKINLEYJUNE 22, 2017



Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story












Photo






Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo speaking last month about mass transit. He has proposed legislation to add two new members to the authority’s board, whom he would select.

Credit
            Hiroko Masuike/The New York Times        



Joseph J. Lhota, who led the Metropolitan Transportation Authority under Gov. Andrew M. Cuomo before leaving for a failed mayoral run in 2013, has been chosen by the governor to return as chairman.The surprise, after-hours announcement was approved late on Wednesday by the State Senate after its Finance Committee voiced its support at an impromptu meeting in the Capitol, during which Mr. Lhota — speaking over Skype — expressed his frustration with problems with the city’s subways.“I know the M.T.A. can do a lot better,” he said.As New Yorkers reach a breaking point over the constant subway delays, Governor Cuomo has moved this week to strengthen his grip on the transportation authority, which runs the city’s transit system.But there is a catch: Mr. Cuomo already controls the agency, and has been calling the shots there for some time.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Mr. Lhota’s nomination came just hours after the authority’s monthly board meeting in Lower Manhattan, in which several members pushed back against Mr. Cuomo’s power grab. He had proposed legislation on Tuesday to add two new members to the authority’s board, whom he would select. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





Board members urged Mr. Cuomo to focus on more pressing issues, including releasing a comprehensive plan to fix the creaky subway system and securing funding for the improvements.The board had been “neutered” by Mr. Cuomo’s growing influence, said Veronica Vanterpool, a member who had been recommended by Mayor Bill de Blasio. Many of the authority’s announcements come from the governor’s office, she said, and his preferences were prioritized in the five-year capital plan.Instead of an increase in the governor’s power, the board needs independence, Ms. Vanterpool said.“We need to ensure the decisions we’re making are on behalf of the public that we serve and not caught up in this political process that we’re often hampered by,” Ms. Vanterpool said.James E. Vitiello, a board member from Dutchess County, said he did not understand why Mr. Cuomo was suddenly trying to change the board’s structure when he had dallied for so long — nearly five months — in naming a permanent leader to run the agency.
Photo






Transit activists in Brooklyn in January. Mr. Cuomo proposed adding two new members to the M.T.A. board, but some board members say that naming a chairman for the authority and working harder for subway improvements are more important.

Credit
            Nicole Bengiveno/The New York Times        


“That just makes no sense to me,” Mr. Vitiello said.With the last scheduled day of the legislative session in Albany dragging past dark on Wednesday, it was unclear if Mr. Cuomo’s legislation might pass or if another bill, to split the roles of chairman and chief executive into two jobs, might. The governor’s father, Gov. Mario M. Cuomo, similarly sought to add members to the board in 1983 to gain a majority, but he backed down after Mayor Edward I. Koch and suburban officials rose up in opposition.Scott Rechler, a new board member appointed by the governor, defended Mr. Cuomo’s legislation. Mr. Rechler said the governor wanted to take full responsibility for the agency — and its challenges. “Let him put 100 percent of his political capital, his expertise, his energy, his relationships into fixing something that is immensely broken,” he said.
