Still, Mr. Cuomo has already exerted a great deal of influence over the authority. He took an active role in the completion of the Second Avenue subway and presided over its lavish opening. He has pressed for electronic tolling at bridges and tunnels and a project to add a track on the Long Island Rail Road.But only recently has he started focusing to a significant degree on the dismal performance of the subway system as riders have begun to accuse the governor of ignoring their plight.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

The authority’s last chairman and chief executive, Thomas F. Prendergast, stepped down in January. The agency’s interim executive director, Veronique Hakim, interviewed for the top job, but Mr. Cuomo’s office apparently opted to go with a proven asset in Mr. Lhota. It was not clear if Mr. Cuomo still intended to create a separate position of chief executive, and if so, if Ms. Hakim would be considered for it.Ms. Vanterpool said board members were often left out of key decisions, including the Long Island Rail Road’s recent move to offer discounts to riders who are diverted during repairs at Pennsylvania Station in New York this summer. The railroad announced the discounts on Tuesday, a day after Mr. Cuomo called for them in a speech.Polly Trottenberg, the city’s transportation commissioner and a board member, offered another example of a time when the board was not consulted. When Mr. Cuomo announced the hiring of a new chief development officer for the authority in April, Ms. Trottenberg said, she learned about the news when she read it in The New York Times.On Wednesday, Ms. Trottenberg said that the governor had already been “hands-on” at the authority and that the city and the mayor also wanted to have a voice in the transit system. She declined to comment on the governor’s push to add two board members, but she had urged Mr. Cuomo to pick a leader for the authority.

Hours later, the governor chose Mr. Lhota, who said he wanted to hire an executive director to run the agency on a daily basis.“There’s a lot of basic work we have to get done,” he said.
Continue reading the main story






